metadata.name: Rangxel #386
Rangxel #258
Rangxel #282
Rangxel #330
Schetsboek  #206
metadata.description:
This is my little tribute to fx (hash and fam).

During an important phone call, I was put on hold. Unconsciously, I began to scribble in my sketchbook. Research shows that scribbling helps focusing, but I dreamed away nonetheless until my pages were filled with scribbles, notes, shopping and a to-do list. 

Mint a uniquely generated page from my non-existent 100% coded sketchbook (except text typography). 

The page may contain many scribbles and drawings in pen, felt-tip pen, pencil, or less: often references to artists I admire, some in the form of loose scribbles, others in the form of riddles. Those drawings are drawn with code and vary. Unfortunately, I wasn’t able to incorporate tributes to all art and every artist I admire. The sketchbook would never finish. Thanks to rudxane I know that it’s ok to publish something unfinished ;-). 

One reference that appears in every token is to Sol Lewitt, an incredible source of inspiration. His artworks consist of instructions. Your sketch book pages contain instructions too. You will find the instructions for the artwork scribbled on your unique page by pressing i.

Curious how the work would look without the ‘distracting’ scribbles and coffee stains? Press ‘a’, ‘w’, or ‘g’. 

800 x 800 px

Press ‘s’ to save an image.

Made with p5js and the amazing p5.scribble.js library by Janneck Wullschleger.

Font used: Sacremento-Regular under the SIL Open Font License (OFL).

See license.md for the licenses of both.

Thank you all!

metadata.name: MEDUSA #126
metadata.description:
Medusa is a generative piece playing with noise, cosinus/sinus functions and lines.  The radius, frequency and amplitude of each lines are generated for each token, along with the color theme and the lines's count. Some rare items are available.

 Created by Quentin Hocdé, in Amalfi (Italia).

metadata.name: Blooming dancers #36
metadata.description:
Inspired by the similarity between a dancer's dress and a blooming flower.

It's an homage to art and nature, with exclusive features including :

- A choice between 12 modern and 12 rarer Artist inspired color palettes (Thanks to http://www.colorlisa.com/)
- 1 to 5 dancers
- Various Soft and Hard framing options
- A unique full canvas system which allows the collector to display on portrait, landscape or square screen the art
- A lot of line and background style variations.

The art is better viewed in full screen, captures don't display the fine details

patxol - 2022

Made with p5js

metadata.name: Unknown Monuments #52
metadata.description:
That Monument belongs to someone.

.Four seasons of the year.
.Three Forest Densities.
.Nine monuments.
.Can be actived or inactive.
.Rare raining.

-

Monuments often seem peaceful,
Perhaps they bring mute regrets,
Maybe bloody words and gestures,
Perhaps even peace itself!

They are always rich and full of glory.
They always cry out to the history of a people

One of these days I'll build a monument.
Not a monument for what's great.
But a monumento for the misunderstood.
A monument of clay and blood.
A monument of old newspaper pieces,
A monument of bones and gold,
A monument covered in autumn leaves,
A damp monument,

Because it brings tears.

-

by Gen Doodler | twitter.com/GenDoodler

metadata.name: the endless dance #59
metadata.description:
“We thought of life by analogy with a journey, a pilgrimage, which had a serious purpose at the end, and the thing was to get to that end, success or whatever it is, maybe heaven after you’re dead. But we missed the point the whole way along. It was a musical thing and you were supposed to sing or to dance while the music was being played.” ― Alan Watts

Controls
spacebar: pause/unpause
mousedown: overdraw
x key: clear canvas

enjoy the dance

metadata.name: ℜ●𝖗𝕊⊂⧦▲𝕔𝖞 #57
metadata.description:
Human feature detection theory proposes that the human nervous system sorts and
filters incoming stimuli to allow a human to make sense of visual information,
though it might be just random visual appearances.

This series takes inspiration from the psychological Rorschachtest introduced
by Swiss psychologist Hermann Rorschach. Each token features a generative system
which tries to achieve such a cognitive stimulus to elicit Pareidolia or
clustering illusions.

The underlying algorithm uses an autonomous agent to create initial paint
strokes. The resultant pattern is used to perform a reaction diffusion
simulation controlled by four different noise functions.

Javascript, WebGL, THREE.js
Guido Schmidt
fxhash.xyz 2021/12/17
